The reasons for such optimism, in each other, and pessimism in others?
Biometrics will be based on new technologies, which will enable new services to be provided to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most used biometric data are fingerprints, hand contours and venous network of palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its own constraints.
"For example, some people who work concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are unreadable," says Philippe Robin, technical director of the field of identity at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection as well as the verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand involve a voluntary and specific gesture of the people.
It is both security - we cannot capture this data on their own - and a disadvantage: the procedure must sometimes be repeated and therefore takes time.
Consequently, research has been carried out for twenty years on other approaches, such as facial or iris recognition (colored part of the eye).
As a result of increased sensor accuracy and computer computing capacity required for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
The accuracy of facial recognition has been multiplied by ten over the last five years, calculated Cyrille Bataller, director of the Accenture R&D laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the United Kingdom and Holland have deployed automatic border posts using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
"Today, we do research on the recognition of voice or how to walk with sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment," said Sridhar Iyangar, Director of Security Research at Intel Labs.
Unique and infallible marker, DNA also arouses hopes and concerns.
"In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered as the ultimate biometric data," confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavenier, Director of Studies, Innovation and Prospectives at CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC proposes to the judicial police services a suitcase costing 90,000 euros to analyze DNA samples in the place of a crime and in an hour.
The uses of biometrics are divided into two groups: identification (recognizing one person among others) and authentication (to ensure that the person is the person she claims to be).
The identification concerned so far the issue of identity papers: we must confront the biometric elements (prints, photos, iris) with the information that the state has on all the citizens already set.
This makes it possible to ensure that a person does not attempt to usurp someone else's identity.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC thus offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or store.
"We will recover the images of surveillance cameras and compare them to the photos of celebrities who freely travel over the Internet," explains Dany Nassif, responsible for commercial development at NEC France for biometric identification solutions.
Another use: take a picture of a guy who tails in a store, follow his progression through facial recognition and calculate waiting time.
Authentication initially involved physical access (frontier, protected premises, canteens...) or logic (opening a computer).
More recently, the presence control was added.
"A biometric sharper avoids the phenomenon of the boyfriend who points for another," explains Cyrille Bataller, Accenture.
But, increasingly, authentication will also concern transactions, especially those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from some distributors by introducing his card and placing his hand on a biometric player: this gesture replaces the secret code hit.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoulême by the Natural Security company in partnership with banks and major distribution teachers: at the time of paying in-store with its bank card, the client does not type his code, but introduces his finger into a reader that scans the veins.
The experiment is planned to last six months.
If successful, biometric readers could soon arrive at French merchants.
Hints to Ensure Users
There are three ways to make biometrics attractive to the general public.
The first is to explain that she can make time.
"If, thanks to biometry, a client stays in cash for thirty seconds less, it's appreciated," explains the director of a large area.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer tailored options.
And finally, make sure that the precautions taken to protect databases are taken forward.
"Digital fingerprints are stored on a first server; the identities of people are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure box, which is blocked if you try to move it," says Philippe Robin, from Thales.
However, because of a lack of in-depth studies, it is impossible to know whether these speeches really convince users.
Privacy specialists continue to worry.
"The progress of facial recognition, the multiplication of surveillance cameras and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa, made me fear the worst: widespread surveillance," Andrew Patrick, from the Office of the Privacy Commissioner in Canada.
