Scientists have just highlighted how a dog's tail movements are related to its mood.
Previous studies revealed that happy dogs moved their tails further to the right (from the dog's point of view), while nervous dogs moved it further to the left.
But now scientists say that dogs can detect and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trente, said: "Everyone knows that, in humans, the left side and the right side of the brain are involved differently in stimuli that awaken positive or negative emotions."
Here, we tried to see what was in other species.
He added that as in men, in dogs the right side of the brain was responsible for movement to the left and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to disorderly tail movements from other dogs, researchers followed animals watching movies where other dogs were.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
It will certainly not take long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes on one side and sometimes on the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: "We have presented to dogs the movies where other dogs were – either a naturalist version or a silhouette to avoid any other confusion factors – and we have been able to traffic the tail movement and present it as going more to the left or right."
When the animals saw a dog without expression rip the tail to the right (from the dog's point of view that rips the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they found a tail drifting mainly to the left (once again from the dog's point of view that removes the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think that the dogs deliberately communicated with each other through these movements.
Rather, he thinks that dogs know by experience the movements they should or should not be worried about.
He added: "If you encounter other dogs on several occasions and if you notice that, most of the time, the movement of their tail to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and that the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react to this experience."
Researchers indicate that results could enable owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand their animals' emotions.
The expert in canine behaviour John Bradshaw, a guest professor at the University of Bristol School of Veterinary Sciences, said this was not the first study to examine the importance of the left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team at Lincoln University discovered that the dogs were turning their heads to the left when they looked at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a cheerful dog.
And in another scientific study carried out by Victoria University in Canada, he said: "The dogs went more easily to a robot dog when their tail moved to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming anxious - the opposite of what is in the Italian study."
He indicated that the differences could come from the fact that dogs who participated in the various studies did not consider the animals of the films or the robots dogs as being dogs.
A study on how dogs react to real dogs might be useful, he explained.
"Although many elements, recorded in different mammals, indicate that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be specified – and the dogs are no exception," he said.
However, given the ease with which their behaviour can be recorded, it will certainly not take long before we understand why their tail sometimes moves on one side and sometimes on the other.
