This is the case of the new species that has just been identified.
Ten years ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily: Pacific bossed dolphins and Atlantic borough whales.
Recent analyses made it possible to distinguish four species.
Why is this an important discovery as claimed by the Wildlife Conservation Society?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know these genetic differences in order to protect the species and hence its genetic variability.
If this population had been known for a long time by researchers, they did not know that it was part of a new species, only present at that place.
Therefore, if a problem of massive mortality caused by a viral epidemic or accidental capture occurs in the region, we may have a problem with the extinction of a species, rather than with a local disappearance of a population of a more widespread species on Earth.
