A species is considered threatened or endangered by the number of existing individuals on Earth, i.e. stock, and the possibility of recovery from neighbouring stocks.
With regard to the species Sousa chinensis, whose population of the new discovered species has emerged, its stock has automatically become smaller, making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are located at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats, where there are numerous genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This gene brewing limits the creation of new species.
On the other hand, more closed ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which can eventually lead to the creation of new species.
We need to know that the marine environment is the least well-known environment.
