This is not something you have the opportunity to do in America when you are a medical student in the second year.
Volunteer students usually pay for their travel to Cameroon, and often arrive with medical equipment collected.
But once in Yaoundé, their pensions, their transportation and education are taken care of by Dr. Bwelle.
"He's a hero, there's no doubt about it," said Katie O'Malley.
He gives his life for this association, and his desire to help the Cameroonian people is not close to extinction.
For Dr. Bwelle, the relatively constant workload is not a problem.
Helping others to live happily by keeping his promise to his father is something that brings him immense joy.
"I am so happy when I do this work," added Mr. Bwelle.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
To make people laugh and to relieve pain are the reasons why I am motivated to do that.
